ecomes evident is that, even though he was writing at a time when many writers and artists were less inclined to deal directly with the things of the world, Lorca maintained a profound interest in the human subject and in the world around him. It is this interest, the book argues, in tandem with his poetic vision and craft, that ensured his most popular works' enduring, universal appeal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSelf-consciousness (Awareness) in literature. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aModern Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aArtistry.  aFederico García Lorca.  aIdentity.  aModernist.  aPoeta en Nueva York.  aPoetry.  aRomancero Gitano.  aSpanish Poet.  aTragic Plays.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787448216?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787448216423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787448216/original  a978-3-11-143099-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles